        "id": "art_2026-07-11_016",
        "section": "United States",
        "category": "analysis",
        "title": "Rise of the Gen-Z Luddite",
        "title_zh": "Z世代卢德派的崛起",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-07-11/16",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\nZ世代作为完全的智能手机原住民,正在掀起一场反科技的「卢德运动」,他们质疑智能手机、社交媒体和人工智能对生活与就业的负面影响,纷纷尝试回归更接近模拟时代的离线生活方式。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n\n1. 「夏季卢德节」(Summer of Ludd)于2026年6月28日至7月5日在纽约举办,活动禁止携带手机,无社交媒体宣传,依靠海报和口碑传播,口号包括「解放iPad婴儿」和「不要Gemini、GPT、Grok、Claude」,到场者多为二十多岁的年轻人,人数虽少但反映出Z世代对科技日益增长的矛盾情绪。\n\n2. 多项民调印证Z世代对科技的厌倦:2024年Harris民调显示近四分之一Z世代希望智能手机从未被发明;Pew研究中心发现超过半数Z世代支持禁止16岁以下人群使用社交媒体;Marist民调显示70%的Z世代认为人工智能将对就业产生负面影响。\n\n3. 当代年轻卢德派并非全盘否定数字世界,而是特别反对追踪工具、侵入性算法以及设备对社交生活的侵蚀,这与19世纪因纺织业机械化而抗议的原始卢德派在动机上有所差异——前者更关注生活方式而非生计。\n\n4. Z世代正以多种方式回归模拟生活:翻盖手机和盒式磁带销量上升,新兴「卢德俱乐部」鼓励暂时放弃智能手机和社交媒体,园艺、解谜等触觉活动被网红重新包装为「奢华」生活方式,Pinterest以「关乎生活而非点赞」为卖点吸引用户。\n\n5. 颇具反讽意味的是,「线下潮流」正通过「线上渠道」流行:一条鼓励改用旧款iPod的TikTok视频获得300万次观看(有评论者询问该设备如何在没有流媒体的情况下使用);「夏季卢德节」本身也有一名与会者自认是小组的「指定手机使用者」协助导航;现年25岁的Nick Plante三年前放弃智能手机后表示自己重新能够读完一本书,并感叹「这是我人生中感觉最好的时刻」。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n原文未涉及明显争议。\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n基于Z世代对科技的反感情绪持续蔓延,立法者或将更积极推动针对未成年人的社交媒体禁令,科技公司也可能被迫在隐私保护、算法透明度与青少年安全方面作出更大让步,以挽回这一代消费者的信任。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">United States</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | Tech and its discontents</span></p>\n<h1>Rise of the Gen-Z Luddite</h1>\n<h3>Resistance to tech is brewing among digital natives</h3>\n<h3>July 9th 2026</h3>\n<p>“We will free the iPad babies,” went one chant at the Summer of Ludd. “No Gemini, no GPT, no Grok, no Claude,” went another. The festival for big-tech sceptics, held in New York from June 28th to July 5th, stayed mostly true to its principles. Phones were banned. The event had no social-media presence. Organisers relied on posters and word of mouth to publicise the festival. Perhaps as a result, the crowds were small. Yet those who came, most of them in their 20s, reflect an ambivalence about technology that is increasingly common among Generation Z.</p>\n<p>Members of this cohort are the first to have grown up entirely in the age of the smartphone. Now many are reflecting on what it has cost them. In 2024 nearly a quarter of Gen Z-ers told Harris, a pollster, that they wished smartphones had never been invented. More recent polling by Pew found that over half support banning under-16s from social media. Many are trying to reduce their own screen time, deleting apps or setting limits. Others, like the self-described Luddites in Manhattan, go further. At one point during the festival, devices were “executed” after standing trial.</p>\n<p>The original Luddites were 19th-century textile workers who resented the mechanisation of their industry. They were not opposed to all technology, but feared for their livelihoods. Today’s young Luddites do not shun the digital world entirely, but object to tracking tools, invasive algorithms and devices’ effect on their social lives. Artificial intelligence has added another fear: 70% of Gen Z think AI will have a negative impact on jobs, according to Marist.</p>\n<p>Some Gen Z-ers are trying to lead more analogue lives, swapping screen time for offline pursuits. Sales of flip phones and cassette tapes have risen. New “Luddite clubs” encourage people to give up their smartphones and social media, at least for a while. Ironically, going offline is being popularised online. Influencers post about gardening and puzzles as antidotes to doomscrolling, reframing tactile activities as a “luxury” lifestyle. A video on TikTok, encouraging a switch to an old iPod, has 3m views. (One commenter asks how the device works without streaming.) Pinterest, a social network, is courting users by promising “it’s about life, not likes”.</p>\n<p>Even the Summer of Ludd is not entirely free from the tensions of the modern world. One attendee admits she was her group’s “designated smartphone user”, helping everyone else navigate the city. Still, the Luddites believe in their cause. Since giving up his smartphone three years ago, Nick Plante, 25, reports milestones such as being able to finish a book again. “This is the best I’ve felt, probably ever in my life.” <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>Stay on top of American politics with The US in brief, our daily newsletter with fast analysis of the most important political news, and <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/newsletters/checks-and-balance\">Checks and Balance</a>, a weekly note that examines the state of American democracy and the issues that matter to voters.</p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//united-states/2026/07/09/rise-of-the-gen-z-luddite\">https://www.economist.com//united-states/2026/07/09/rise-of-the-gen-z-luddite</a> </p>",
