        "title": "A century on, Pilates flexes its muscles",
        "title_zh": "百年普拉提再展雄风",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-07-11/70",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\n普拉提这门诞生于1926年的古老运动在百年后迎来全球热潮，成为2025年增长最快的健身类型，但市场饱和风险与高昂价格或将成为其扩张瓶颈。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n1. 普拉提热度飙升，数据亮眼：在ClassPass健身课程预约平台上，普拉提成为2025年全球增长最快的健身类型；Google上「Reformer Pilates」的搜索量也创下历史新高，社交媒体上肌肉男在课堂上挣扎咒骂的视频尤其容易走红。\n2. 商业版图快速扩张：根据MMCG地产咨询公司的估算，美国最大普拉提连锁Club Pilates的门店从2015年不足50家激增至2024年的1100多家；洛杉矶Bodyline工作室的Maria Leone感叹，普拉提工作室的开店速度堪比当年的冻酸奶店和洗车店。\n3. 历史源远流长：德国健身爱好者Joseph Pilates在一战期间被关押于英国战俘营时创立该体系，最初将其命名为「Controlology」，1926年在纽约开设首家工作室，核心理念是强化肌肉同时减轻关节压力。\n4. 独特卖点吸引多元人群：普拉提强调力量与柔韧兼具，对不愿在健身房「举铁」的女性尤其有吸引力（来源：普拉提教练Bethan Dando）；其改善灵活性、辅助肌肉恢复、强化关节的功效使其成为力量训练的良好补充，篮球运动员LeBron James与英式橄榄球运动员George Ford均认可其在伤后康复中的作用。\n5. 增长隐忧初现：ClassPass母公司Playlist的Jeff Bladt警告，部分市场供给增速已超过需求，饱和点或将临近；纽约一节Reformer课程价格高达约50美元，令不少消费者望而却步。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n原文未涉及明显争议。主要提及发展隐忧：ClassPass母公司Playlist的Jeff Bladt指出部分市场供给增速超过需求，饱和或将到来；纽约单节课约50美元的高价也让部分消费者却步。\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n基于文章事实，普拉提品牌目前仍处强势阶段，但若供给过剩问题持续加剧，部分市场可能出现工作室整合或价格调整；男性参与者的增加与社交媒体传播效应可能继续推动其在大众健身市场扩张，成为传统力量训练的补充而非替代。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">Culture</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | The resistance movement</span></p>\n<h1>A century on, Pilates flexes its muscles</h1>\n<h3>An old exercise method is newly trendy</h3>\n<h3>July 9th 2026</h3>\n<p>ATTENDING A Pilates class means reckoning with your own feebleness. The Reformer machine—a moving carriage attached to various springs and straps—looks rather like a torture device (and, depending on your instructor’s inclination, it can be). The idea is to perform slow, controlled movements such as lunges using springs as resistance; it does not sound too bad. But then, out of nowhere, you are dripping with sweat and your knees are shaking as if you are performing a bad <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/britain/2025/06/04/a-new-london-attraction-hopes-to-revive-interest-in-elvis\">Elvis</a> impersonation.</p>\n<p>Perhaps it is cool to be humbled, because Pilates—which can be performed on a mat as well as a machine—is absolutely on fire (emphasis on the abs). It was the fastest-growing workout type worldwide in 2025 on ClassPass, a fitness-session booking platform. Earlier this year Google searches for Reformer Pilates hit an all-time high. On social media videos often go viral—particularly ones of muscly men struggling and cursing through a session.</p>\n<p>MMCG, a property consultancy, has estimated that Club Pilates, America’s largest studio <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/leaders/2026/05/28/why-the-world-needs-more-franchises\">franchise</a>, grew from fewer than 50 branches in 2015 to more than 1,100 in 2024. “People are opening Pilates studios the way they opened frozen yogurt places and car washes,” says Maria Leone of Bodyline, a studio in Los Angeles, a city renowned for toned, beach-ready bodies.</p>\n<p>This is not to say Pilates is new: in fact, Joseph Pilates (pictured below) opened the first studio in New York in 1926. A German fitness fanatic, he devised the system while interned in a British camp during the <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/europe/2018/11/08/lessons-from-history-100-years-after-the-armistice\">first world war</a>. He initially dubbed his exercises, which strengthen muscles but minimise stress on the joints, “Contrology”. Unsurprisingly the name did not stick.</p>\n<p>The appeal of Pilates, then and now, is its emphasis on power and flexibility. The rewards of strength training are widely known and this format appeals to women who may not enjoy pumping iron in the gym, reckons Bethan Dando, a Pilates instructor. Its reputation for improving mobility, aiding muscle recovery and strengthening joints also makes it an effective complement to weightlifting, which could explain the rising interest from men. It has been endorsed by athletes including <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/culture/2023/12/23/the-contrasting-paths-of-michael-jordan-and-lebron-james\">LeBron James</a>, an American basketball player, and George Ford, an English rugby player, who reckon Pilates helps with injury rehabilitation and keeps them supple.</p>\n<p>Can the craze stretch further? Jeff Bladt of Playlist, ClassPass’s parent company, says that in some markets supply growth is outpacing that of demand, so a saturation point may be near. Many tremble at the cost: in New York, a single Reformer class will set you back around $50. But the market is not hamstrung yet. Its fans may feel weak, but the Pilates brand is strong. <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//culture/2026/07/06/a-century-on-pilates-flexes-its-muscles\">https://www.economist.com//culture/2026/07/06/a-century-on-pilates-flexes-its-muscles</a> </p>",
